# Performance and accessibility priorities

Treat **frontend performance**, **database performance**, and **accessible UI** as top priorities on every change — not as optional follow-ups.

## Frontend performance

- Avoid unnecessary client JS, blocking scripts, and layout thrashing
- Prefer efficient assets (fingerprinting, caching headers, compressed CSS) and avoid shipping unused GOV.UK or app JS/CSS
- Watch Core Web Vitals risks: large assets, long tasks, layout shift, late LCP
- Prefer progressive enhancement on macro-rendered markup over heavy client rendering

## Database performance

- Prefer indexed, selective Prisma/PostgreSQL queries; avoid N+1 and unbounded `findMany` without pagination or limits
- Use transactions only where needed; avoid chatty round-trips when a single query or `$transaction` batch is enough
- Do not add migrations or schema changes that ignore query cost or lock impact without calling them out
- Prefer Nest/Prisma patterns already in the stack over ad-hoc SQL that bypasses reviewable query shapes

## Accessible UI

- Prefer GOV.UK Frontend macros, CSS, and JS so accessibility patterns from the Design System are preserved
- Keep keyboard, focus, error summary, labels, and skip-link behaviour intact when changing templates or app JS
- Do not “fix” accessibility by breaking GOV.UK Frontend to satisfy a single axe rule — see `.cursor/rules/prefer-govuk-over-axe.mdc`
- Manual and automated checks should remain green for journeys you touch; if a conflict is intentional, document it

## On every change

- Ask whether the change hurts load time, query cost, or accessibility before shipping
- Prefer the smaller, clearer fix that keeps all three priorities intact over clever but expensive alternatives
- Call out residual performance or a11y risks in summaries when they remain
